<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Submission from the Electrical Safety Roundtable</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ubmission from the Electrical Safety Roundtable</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (BRC 41)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The Electrical Safety Roundtable (ESR) was initially formed in response to widespread concern over poor promotion of competent registered electricians</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and a lack of Building Regulation enforcement. It is run by and independent secretariat has four board members and is chaired by Chris Bielby, Chair of Trustees at the Gas Safety Trust.  The group works collaboratively with industry and other relevant interested stakeholders to improve electrical safety in the home. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The ESR notes that whilst awareness of the Building Regulations and Competent Person Schemes has been historically low, improving enforcement of building regulations and simplifying the message to consumers of the benefits of using a Competent, Registered Electrician is the best approach to improving this. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Historically, the standards required of competent electricians have varied. The ESR believes that this will be remedied to a significant degree by the new DCLG conditions of authorisation that all CPS providers must adhere to by June 2014 which include compliance with EAS 2012 standards, which have been revised and improved compared to the 2010 ones. However, we also note the current inadequacy of the specification’s emphasis on competent </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">enterprises </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">rather than individuals. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The ESR is of the view that requiring all electricians carrying out notifiable work under the Building Regulations to demonstrate their competence individually would improve levels of safety, as is the case in Ireland.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">DCLG currently sets strict, uniform terms for all Competent Person Scheme providers</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> and t</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">here is evidence of the positive impact of competition between CPS providers (EC Harris Report 2012)</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The ESR believes that better promotion of competent, registered electricians is vital to improving levels of consumer awareness and therefore safety. It </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">supports the idea of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">a single consumer facing register, fed into by all electrical Competent Person Scheme providers to retain the positive aspects of competition.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The ESR considers that the issue of DCLG supervision has already been addressed; from June 2014, the responsibility for scheme supervision will transfer to UKAS and all scheme providers will be required to achieve/maintain UKAS accreditation to standard BS EN ISO/IEC 17065:2012 by that date.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> As a minimum, UKAS has committed to conducting surveillance of CPS providers annually and ensuring they are fully</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> r</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e-assessed every fourth year.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Section 1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Background to the Electrical Safety Roundtable</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The Electrical Safety Roundtable was formed in response to widespread concern over poor promotion of competent registered electricians and a lack of Building Regulation enforcement. It is run by an independent secretariat; has 4 board members and is chaired by Chris Bielby, Chair of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Trustees at the Gas Safety Trust.  The roundtable aims to work collaboratively with industry and other relevant stakeholders to improve electrical safety in the home. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Currently signed up participants of the ESR include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Chief Fire Officers Association</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Stroma</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BEAMA</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">BSI</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">JELF</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Benchmark</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Megger</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">OFTEC</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">NHIC</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">LABC </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">NAPIT</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">NAPIT Trade Association</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">City and Guilds</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Other stakeholders also support the ESR by attending meetings and contributing to the work of the Group. These include the All Party Parliamentary Home Safety Group, Rospa and Trading Standards/Buy with Confidence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Section 2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The committee is keen to establish the extent to which members of the public are aware of the competent persons scheme and that certain domestic electrical works need to be reviewed and certified to meet the requirements of Building Regulations </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">2.1 Public awareness of the Competent Person Scheme has been historically low. The Electrical Safety Council commissioned nationwide research, during the process of consultation for the recent revisions to Part P, to assess awareness of the Building Regulations. It found that only 20 per cent of respondents had heard of Part P of the Building Regulations. Moreover, only 25 per cent were aware of the need to notify major electrical installation work to the Local Authority Building Control.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> The recent findings of an ElectricSafe survey campaign suggest the figure for recognition of Competent Person Schemes may even be lower, with only 18.71 per cent of 668 respondents saying they had heard of them. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">2.2 This may be the result of a number of influencing factors, including:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The lack of a sustained public awareness campaign</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> for the Competent Person Scheme.  This is being addressed; the DCLG current conditions of authorisation (2012), requires CPS providers to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">promote the development and growth of the scheme to potential members and its use to customers.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The complexities of which work needs to be notified</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> under Part P are difficult for the householder to grasp. The recent (April 2013) changes to Part P, which has reduced the number of areas in homes in England that work needs to be notified (despite the fact it must still comply with BS 7671) may have added to this difficulty, especially when the same </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">changes have not be introduced in Wales. </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Low levels of enforcement of Part P</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> also contributes to customers  lack of awareness of the requirements. Non-compliant  work is often not picked up and the householder may not be aware that electrical work must comply with the Building Regulations.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> A report on Part P, commissioned by DCLG, noted: </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">“The building control enforcement landscape is one of extremes. On the one hand there is an extremely, perhaps unduly, low level of formal enforcement applied. Against this there is a massive (5million p.a.) portfolio of informal compliance interventions being conducted.”</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">2.3   </span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The ESR does not support the reduction in the number of notifiable areas in PART P, especially due to the increased risk to safety due to the proximity of water in kitchens and outdoor areas remains. The ESR is also concerned about the confusion which is caused to both installers and consumers due to the different requirements in England and Wales.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">2.4 Public awareness of the competent persons scheme and of the need to review and certify certain domestic work would be improved by having one register, where householders can find a competent</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> registered electrician.  All CPS providers would need to feed into this one register and advertise it in order for this approach to be effective. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Section 3 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Committee is keen to establish the extent to which those carrying out electrical works are adequately trained to meet the requirements of the Building Regulations and the extent to which all those working for a company are brought up to the same level of skills. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Adequacy of training</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">3.1 Levels of training and/or experience required for CPS registration have historically varied widely. However the ESR is confident that this variation is currently being addressed. In the DCLG conditions of authorisation 2012, CPS providers for the electrical industry must comply with the Electrotechnical Assessment Specification, which are the minimum technical competencies (MTC’s).</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> Competent Person Scheme providers are required to meet this minimum standard of entry by June 2014. There are a number of different routes to competency that satisfy this specification, all of which require significant knowledge and understanding of current requirements for electrical installations and evidence of work carried out that demonstrates competency in the scope of electrical work for which they have applied.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">  The ESR believe that CPS policing of the experience and training requirements set out in this document, combined with proper UKAS supervision, will improve on any previous inadequacies.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">3.2 There have also been recent efforts within the industry to further tighten certain routes to competency through the EAS standards e.g. those applying to a CPS provider having undertaken  a 5 day training course for example, must also provide evidence to demonstrate 2 years of appropriate experience. (See appendix 4a- option 4, EAS 2012)</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">3.3 It is important that the cost involved for an electrician to be deemed competent is minimised- this is one of the reasons why having a number of certification bodies is essential- however the level of safety afforded to the householder is paramount.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Individual Competence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">3.4 The Electrotechnical Assessment Specification is an industry specific guide to the Minimum Technical Competencies required under DCLG conditions of authorisation. It was put together by bodies representing electrical installation industry and consumer safety interests in order to enhance the standard of safety of </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Electrical installation work.</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">he ESR is concerned that the interpretation of BS EN 45011, set out in the EAS, includes the understanding that these competency requirements apply to </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">enterprises</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> as opposed to individuals. This means scheme providers are currently only obligated to ensure and assess the competence of one individual in each company, the Qualified Supervisor (QS).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">3.5 This individual is able to sign off the work of the other electricians working for the registered enterprise, which may or may not have demonstrated an equivalent level of competence. </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">The current conditions of authorisation for scheme providers state that the scheme providers “shall, under a risk-based approach, undertake a minimum of one on-site inspection of each </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">member’s</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> work every three years.” But the current interpretation iterated above means that the member is currently defined as the enterprise rather than the individual by the majority of CPS providers, in other words, regular assessments and satisfaction of initial entry criteria are only required of the </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">Qualified Supervisor</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">3.6 One competent, registered electrician being able to sign off the work of those who may not have demonstrated their competence has the potential to be dangerous. This is especially true if the Qualified Supervisor does not inspect the job during and after completion, or signs off work as compliant without actually checking it; which has been known to happen. One way to improve that system would be to ensure that the QS being assessed was able to provide not only the names of his/her operatives but original copies of their qualification certificates and copies of the calibration certificates of their test equipment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">3.7 The ESR believes that requiring each electrician, carrying out work which is notifiable to building regulations, within a registered company to be assessed to verify their ongoing competency would be another way to improve on this model.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Section 4</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The committee is keen to establish the extent to which those carrying out electrical works, to which the Building Regulations apply, review or have their work reviewed to ensure that it meets the requirements of the Regulations.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">4.1 As highlighted in 3.5 above, the QS model could in some instances mean that some employees of registered companies may be carrying out electrical works to which the Building Regulations apply </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">without having had regular assessments to ensure their work meets the requirements of these regulations.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">4.2 The ESR is of the view that requiring all electricians carrying out notifiable work under the Building Regulations to demonstrate their competence individually would improve levels of safety as is the case in Ireland.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">4.3 As stated above Competent Person Scheme providers may have slightly different policies and procedures. However, from June 2014, they must all “under a risk-based approach, undertake a minimum of one on-site inspection of each member’s work every three years” in line with DCLG’s conditions of authorisation.</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> An example of what an inspector would ask to see during this assessment would be a minimum of two new circuits, recently completed by the electrician. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Section 5</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The committee is keen to establish the effect of competition between accreditation bodies, and the two separate registers of electricians, on the standards of review of domestic electrical work</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Competent Person Schemes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">5.1 It has been highlighted in a report, published during the 2012 review of Part P of the Building Regulations, that the competition between scheme providers has had a positive impact on the cost to electricians who opt to join.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">5.2 The report, compiled by EC Harris on behalf of DCLG, noted on page 9 : </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">“The  cost  to  contractors  of  participation  in  a  Competent  Persons  Scheme appears to  have been overestimated.  This seems to be due to competition between the various schemes (NICEIC, NAPIT etc).”</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Electricians Registers </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">5.3 Both registers exist to promote electricians that are assessed regularly in compliance with the standards set out in the DCLG’s conditions of authorisation.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">5.4 The two registers impact on these standards seems only to be the promotion of competent, registered electricians to householders.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">5.5 The ESR is of the opinion that better promotion of competent, registered electricians is vital to improving levels of consumer awareness and therefore safety. We propose that a single register, fed into by all electrical Competent Person Scheme providers to retain the positive aspects of competition would represent the best conclusion to this debate for all concerned. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Section 6</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The committee is keen to establish the adequacy of the supervision by DCLG of the accreditation schemes. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">6.1 This point is being addressed via t</span><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">he Governments response</span><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">recommendation 8 of the</span><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Communities and Local Government Select Committee Report: Building Regulations applying to electrical and gas installation and repairs in dwellings</span><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> (July 2012) – a recommendation that current arrangements need greater independent supervision to offset the pressures to compromise safety standards –</span><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">stated:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“The Government accepts this recommendation. There are nine [sic - currently 7] Competent Person Schemes authorised for Part P of the Building Regulations. It is true that most of the income of the scheme providers comes from fees levied on installers registered with the schemes. The Department has recently published new conditions of authorisation for competent person self-certification schemes.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><h1 style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h1><h1 style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">One of the changes is that all scheme providers will have to seek and achieve UKAS (United Kingdom Accreditation Service) accreditation to standard EN 45011 [sic - now </span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">EN ISO/IEC 17065:2012]</span><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">, which sets out </span><span style="color:#323232; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">general requirements for bodies</span><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="color:#323232; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">operating product certification systems</span><span style="color:#211d1e; font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">. In future, UKAS will regularly monitor the operation of the schemes, which will provide independent supervision of the schemes and help ensure that there are no conflicts of interest.”</span></h1><h1 style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">6.2 Therefore, the Government has already accepted that DCLG may not be best placed to supervise the schemes adequately and, as the scheme providers are currently in a transition period to complying with UKAS requirements, are doing something to rectify this.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">6.3 The implications of this change are that, from June 2014, the responsibility for scheme supervision will transfer to UKAS and all scheme providers will be required to achieve and maintain UKAS accreditation to standard BS EN ISO/IEC 17065:2012 by that date.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> As a minimum, UKAS has committed to conducting surveillance of CPS providers annually and ensuring they are fully</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> r</span><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">e-assessed every fourth year.</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt"> The ESR understands that all CPS providers should currently either have gained or be in the process of gaining UKAS accreditation under DCLGs current Conditions of Authorisation. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">6.4 The ESR supports this change, and hopes that it will result in improved supervision of CPS providers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Please note this response reflects the agreed views of the group but may not necessarily reflect the views of individual members.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Where this document uses the term “electrician”  this refers to a “Registered Installer” as defined by DCLG.</span></p><p style="font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> http://www.safeelectric.ie/</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Communities and Local Government., BUILDING REGULATIONS: COMPETENT PERSON SELF-CERTIFICATION SCHEMES - CONDITIONS OF AUTHORISATION FROM 6 JUNE 2012 </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/building-regulations-competent-person-schemes"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/building-regulations-competent-person-schemes</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:9pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">EC Harris (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">January 2012).,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Economic and analytical support for impact assessment of proposals to amend the Building Regulations in 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Department for Communities and Local Government</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Communities and Local Government., BUILDING REGULATIONS: COMPETENT PERSON SELF-CERTIFICATION SCHEMES - CONDITIONS OF AUTHORISATION FROM 6 JUNE 2012 </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/building-regulations-competent-person-schemes"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/building-regulations-competent-person-schemes</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> UKAS Agreement (p2, 1.5) </span><a href="http://www.ukas.com/about-accreditation/apply-for-accreditation/accreditation-category-forms.asp"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ukas.com/about-accreditation/apply-for-accreditation/accreditation-category-forms.asp</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Electrical Safety Council consultation response </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">on the Government’s proposed changes to Part P of the Building Regulations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://ow.ly/qavbF"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://ow.ly/qavbF</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Communities and Local Government., BUILDING REGULATIONS: COMPETENT PERSON SELF-CERTIFICATION SCHEMES - CONDITIONS OF AUTHORISATION FROM 6 JUNE 2012 </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/building-regulations-competent-person-schemes"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/building-regulations-competent-person-schemes</span></a></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.lv.com/about-us/press-media/article/unauthorised-building-works"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.lv.com/about-us/press-media/article/unauthorised-building-works</span></a></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 